<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18440205-798">
               <interp inst="t18440205-798" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18440205"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18440205-798" type="date" value="18440205"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440205-798-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-798-18440205 t18440205-798-offence-1 t18440205-798-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>798. <persName id="def1-798-18440205" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-798-18440205" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-798-18440205" type="age" value="71"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-798-18440205" type="surname" value="GIFFORD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-798-18440205" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE GIFFORD</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440205-798-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440205-798-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440205-798-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp> for feloniously assaulting <persName id="t18440205-name-1476" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1476" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1476" type="surname" value="HOWARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1476" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18440205-798-offence-1 t18440205-name-1476"></join>Henry Howard</persName>, and stabbing and wounding him on the left side of the chest, with intent to do him some grievous bodily harm.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1477" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1477" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1477" type="surname" value="HOWARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1477" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY HOWARD</persName>
                  </hi>. <hi rend="italic">corn-porter, Dale's-place, Stoney-lane, Tooley-street.</hi> On Thursday night, the 18th of Jan., between twelve and one o'clock, I had been taking a drop of porter, but was not the worse for liquor—I met a female, and went with her to a house in Vine-yard, Tooley-street, kept, I believe, by the prisoner—we went into the top room—I took up the poker, joking-like, and swung it round in my hand—I was talking to the female when the prisoner came up, and asked me for the money for the room—I re<lb></lb>fused to give it him just then, and said I would send it down by the young woman in a minute or two (I had not been in the room three minutes when the prisoner came in) he asked for the money again, and I said again that I would send it down—I had the poker in my hand, and was swinging it round, and singing a bit of a song, "The Sprig of Shillalah and Shamrock so Green"—the prisoner then said, "Oh, is that what you mean?" and left the room, shutting the door after him—he came up again with a drawn sword, and said, "Now, you go out of my house"—he made a cut over my head—I held up my arm, and happened to catch the flat part of the sword—he then stabbed me in the breast—I was so irritated I did not exactly see how it was done—I had on this coat and waistcoat—my breast was cut, and bled very much—the poker was at that time in the fender—I put it there while he had gone down for the sword—I did not think he was going to fetch it, or I would not have put it there—I had nothing in my hand at the time I was stabbed—I instantly ran down stairs, and found a policeman—I was taken to Guy's hospital, and had my wound dressed—I remained there till the Monday morning—I was hardly able to move a limb—I then went to Union-hall—I was not able to leave the hospital sooner—I had pains all over my body, limbs and back, and it made me bad all over—I could hardly fetch my breath—I saw the wound—it was a kind of stab—it struck right against my breast bone I expect—I had on this coat—I had made no attempt to strike the prisoner before he made this blow at me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where did you meet with the female? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> At the Waterman's Arms, about eleven o'clock—her name is Simpson—we did not drink together—I had been drinking previously with some friends from nine o'clock—I drank porter—I was not drunk—I had</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050221"></xptr>
               <p>been to the prisoner's house before—I did not brandish the poker round my head, I only twisted it round in my hand, holding it in the middle—I do not know whether that is the way they fight with shillalahs—the prisoner came in while I had it in my hand—I do not know what "Sprig of shiilalah" means—I believe the prisoner said I must either pay him then or go away—I did not then take up the poker, and brandish it—I said, "You can wait a minute or two surely "—I began to brandish it as he was about leaving the room—I did not say, "Show me the man that will turn me out; I will give you a taste of sweet Erin go bragh"—when the prisoner brought the sword up, he said he would give me Erin go bragh—I did not use that expression—I did not in flourishing the poker very nearly strike the girl—I was a distance off both of them—I put down the poker while he was gone for for sword, and never took it up again—I had not the poker in my hand at the time he came in with the sword, nor did I strike a violent blow with it at his head, which he received on the sword—I did not then rush towards him—I ran back—I have known Simpson five or six months, and have been with her to the prisoner's house two or three times—I have been in the habit of giving the money for the room to her to take down to pay, and come up again—I do not think I ever flourished the poker on any previous occasion—I never had any alter<lb></lb>cation with the prisoner before—this room was a double-bedded one, and two persons were in the other bed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1478" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1478" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1478" type="surname" value="SIMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1478" type="given" value="ISABELLA"></interp>ISABELLA SIMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an unfortunate female, and live in Vine-yard, Tooley-street, in the prisoner's house, and have done so five months—on this Thursday night I saw the prosecutor in Vine-yard—he went home with me to the prisoner's house and into the top room—the prisoner came of stairs along with me into the room, and asked the prosecutor if he was going to stop all night—he said, "Yes," and he asked him for the rent of the room—he said, "Do not be so fast," he would send the money down stairs along with me—the prosecutor had a poker in his hand swinging it about, and saying, "Sprig of shillalah and shamrock so green"—he did not make any attempt to strike any body—the prisoner went down stairs, and came up with his sword in about five minutes—he appeared very angry, and said, "Here's for Erin go bragh," rushed forward at the prosecutor, and struck him in the breast with the sword.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was the thrust with the sword almost immediately after he said, "Here's for Erin go bragh?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I had not been drink<lb></lb>ing with the prosecutor—I met him about half an hour before we went to the house—I had seen him in the Waterman's Arms, but did not drink with him at all—I had a little, but not much—at the time the prisoner came up with the sword, the poker was down at the fire-side—the prosecutor put it down immediately the prisoner went down stairs—I was sitting in a chair by the fire when he came up again, and the prosecutor was standing by the fire—he had all his clothes on—there was a male and female in the other bed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1479" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1479" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1479" type="surname" value="M'CORMACK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1479" type="given" value="PATRICK"></interp>PATRICK M'CORMACK</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 59.) On Thursday night, the 18th of Jan., between one and two o'clock, I went to the prisoner's house and asked the prisoner if there had been a disturbance there previously—he said no, every thing had been very quiet—I found this sword in the front par<lb></lb>lour at the head of a bed—the prisoner was in the passage—I only searched that room.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1480" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1480" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1480" type="surname" value="HICKEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1480" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS HICKEY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 152.) I was on duty in Tooley-street on the morning in question, and saw the prosecutor at the top of Vine-yard—he called out "Police"—I went to his assistance—he said he was stabbed—I looked at his breast, and it was all over blood—I directed him to be taken to the hospital, and returned to the prisoner's house—I found him</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050222"></xptr>
               <p>there, and asked if his name was Day—he said, "No"—I asked if he was the landlord of the house—he said, "Yes"—I said, "You are my prisoner; you have stabbed a man"—he said, "Yes I did"—I asked why—he said he did it in his own defence—I said, "Why, did the man strike you?"—he said, "He was going to strike me with the poker"—I took him into custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did he say Howard had rushed forward on him with the poker? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not at that time; he said so at the station, and that he had the sword to protect himself.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1481" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1481" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1481" type="surname" value="PEARSE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1481" type="given" value="HENRY STANLEY ROBERT"></interp>HENRY STANLEY ROBERT PEARSE</persName>
                  </hi>. I was house-surgeon at Guy's Hos<lb></lb>pital—about half-past one on Friday morning, the 19th of Jan., I saw Howard, and discovered a punctured incised wound in his left breast—there had been what surgeons would call very inconsiderable bleeding—I saw this sword the same evening—it was such a wound as might have been inflicted with a thrust from this sword through his clothes—he quitted the hospital on the following Monday—I dressed the wound and attended him—the wound of itself was trivial, and there were no after symptoms at all dangerous—I examined bis clothes—they were cut through—the collar of his coat was twice perforated—I probed the wound—it was very slight—I should say it was nearly an inch deep, but the surrounding parts were much swollen, which made it appear deeper than it really was.</p>
               <p>
